signation of roughly the same period - as a time when same-sex erotic attraction suffused artistic production from Winckelmann's art treatises and Goethe's plays to Friedrich Schlegel's self-reflexive novel Lucinde and Kleist's letters. This volume employs historical, biographical, and textual evidence to paint a cohesive picture of the incontrovertibly sexual nature of male-male and female-female relationships in late-eighteenth- and early-nineteenth-century Germany. The literature of this era bequeathed to us the cultural inventions of Romantic love, classical femininity, the marriage partnership, and the aesthetics of beauty - all, as this volume demonstrates, via and despite the ever-resurgent erotic desire for one's own sex. In the process, it offers radically new readings of canonical authors - including Wieland, Lenz, Goethe, Friedrich Schlegel, and Kleist — in light of the eroticized same-sex relations in their works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aLiterary Studies -- General Criticism and Theory. 7aPOETRY / European / General.2bisacsh1 aGraf, Roman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGustafson, Susan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelfer, Martha B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKord, Susanne T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuzniar, Alice A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuzniar, Alice A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMacLeod, Catriona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPfeiffer, Joachim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichter, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRickels, Laure